It is clear that there is a significant imbalance in the dataset, with some countries having far more entries of precipitation values than other countries. We should keep that in consideration when performing any analysis on this data, especially in country-based analysis.

As part of EDA, we can also see how precipitation changes over time (globally). Precipitation by year can allow us to see potential long-term temporal trends in precipitation.

Here, we see large dips in precipitation around 1991 and 1994, as well as slight dips around 2000 and 2014. These dips may correspond to significant climatic/precipatory events in those years, however, since we do not account for country-level imbalance in this plot, we should be cautious in interpreting these trends. Further, given the counts we see per year for the dataset, these dips and spikes could just be accounted for by the amount of data we have available for those years.

Next, we can examine Year vs Precipitation with a regression using seaborn. We can assess whether there is a systematic temporal trend in precipitation values across countries or not. Given that our previous EDA showed imbalance in the dataset, we should be cautious in interpreting the results of this regression analysis and transform the data accordingly using log transformation.

In[17]:
#plot temporal trend: Year vs. Precipitation across all countries
#since the data is so skewed with some years having little or no data
#we can proceed to log-transform the precipitation values to see if that helps visualize any trends

#log transformation
precipitation_data['log_value'] = np.log1p(precipitation_data['Value'])
sns.regplot(
    data=precipitation_data,
    x="Year",
    y="log_value",
    line_kws={"color": "red"}
)

#since the Year data is being treated as categorical, the scatter and regression do not tell us much. 
#we can proceed with violin plots to see the distribution of precipitation values across different years.
plt.figure(figsize=(15,6))
sns.violinplot(
    data=precipitation_data,
    x='Year',
    y='Value'
)
plt.xticks(rotation=90)
plt.ylabel("Precipitation (million cubic metres)")
plt.title("Distribution of Annual Precipitation by Year")
plt.show()

Given the violin plot output, it would be useful to see if there are significant differences between years in terms of precipitation values. Grouping the years by decade may be best for comparison due to the large number of years in the dataset and the imbalance in data across years. So, we proceed with significant testing using ANOVA to see if there are significant differences in precipitation values across decades.

In[18]:
#create decade column
precipitation_data['Decade'] = (precipitation_data['Year'] // 10) * 10

#group precipitation values by decade
decade_groups = [group['Value'].values for name, group in precipitation_data.groupby('Decade')]

#perform one-way ANOVA
f_stat, p_value = stats.f_oneway(*decade_groups)
print(f"ANOVA F-statistic: {f_stat:.2f}, p-value: {p_value:.4f}")

#replot violin plot by decade
plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
sns.violinplot(data=precipitation_data, x='Decade', y='Value')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.ylabel("Precipitation (million cubic metres)")
plt.title(f"Distribution of Precipitation by Decade\nANOVA p-value = {p_value:.4e}")
plt.show()

ANOVA F-statistic: 0.71, p-value: 0.5482

As seen above, the resulting p-value for our ANOVA is 0.5482. This indicates that there are no statistically significant differences in precipitation values across decades in our dataset. The variation may be accounted for within decades rather than between decades.

Next, we can try to combine visualization of our three variables using Altair. Altair is an interactive visualization tool, so we can use it to explore all three variables at once: time, precipitation, and country.

In[19]:
#plot precipitation by year and country using Altair
#NOTE: CHART IS INTERACTIVE. ZOOM IN BY SCROLLING DOWN AND OUT BY SCROLLING UP. PAN BY CLICKING AND DRAGGING.
#This is an effective way to zoom in on the very dense areas of the plot which are hard to see otherwise
#(around less than 1,000,000 million cubic metres of precipitation)

alt.Chart(precipitation_data).mark_circle(size=60).encode(
    x='Year:O', #treat year as ordinal
    y='Value:Q',
    color='Country or Area:N',
    tooltip=['Country or Area', 'Year', 'Value']
).properties(
    title="Annual precipitation by country over time"
).interactive()
Out[19]:

The interactive nature of the plot helps with visualizing the dense data points. We can see that most countries have precipitation values clustered below 1,000,000 million cubic metres, with potential outliers above that threshold. This once again may just be due to the imbalance in our data set where both certain countries and certain years have far more data points than others.

Finally, we can take a closer look a potential correlations between precipitation in specific countries and certain decades. We can calculate correlations between countries to give us a country-by-country correlation matrix, showing which countries have similar precipitation patterns over time. Then, we can visualize the correlations as a heatmap. This captures potential multivariate relationships as an association between multiple countries precipitation trends.

In[20]:
#use the previously created decade column to create a pivot table for the heatmap
#pivot table of mean precipitation per country per decade
heatmap_data = (
    precipitation_data
    .groupby(['Country or Area', 'Decade'])['Value']
    .mean()
    .reset_index()
    .pivot(index='Country or Area', columns='Decade', values='Value'))

#calculate correlations between countries
country_corr = heatmap_data.T.corr()  # correlation across decades

#keep only countries with most data
top_countries = country_corr.count().sort_values(ascending=False).head(30).index
corr_subset = country_corr.loc[top_countries, top_countries]

#plot correlation heatmap
plt.figure(figsize=(15,12))
sns.heatmap(
    corr_subset,
    cmap='coolwarm',
    center=0,
    linewidths=0.5,
    cbar_kws={'label': 'Precipitation patterns'}
)
plt.title("Correlation of Precipitation Patterns Between Countries Across Decades")
plt.xlabel("Country")
plt.ylabel("Country")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

This condensed heatmap helps us see some strong postive and negative relationships between the top 30 countries based on data availability. For example, we see strong postive relationships between Germany and Honduras (as well as several other countries), indicating that their precipitation patters over decades are similar. We also see strong negative relationships, such as Qatar and Jamaica or Guinea and Panama, indicating that their precipitation patterns are dissimilar/likely opposite. These relationships may be due to geographic/climatic similarities or differences between countries, however further analysis would be needed to confirm this.
